## Steps

### Step 1 — Install Rust toolchain

Install Rust via rustup (https://rustup.rs) if not already installed:

```bash
curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh
```

Ensure the correct stable toolchain is active:

```bash
rustup install stable
rustup default stable
rustup show   # confirm version >= {{rust_version}}
```

---

### Step 2 — Install required cargo tools

```bash
# Vulnerability scanning
cargo install cargo-audit --locked
cargo install cargo-deny --locked

# Unsafe code analysis
cargo install cargo-geiger --locked

# Semver compatibility checking
cargo install cargo-semver-checks --locked

# Coverage (optional but recommended)
cargo install cargo-tarpaulin --locked
```

For fuzzing (requires nightly):

```bash
rustup install nightly
cargo +nightly install cargo-fuzz --locked
```

---

### Step 3 — Clone the repository

Obtain the repository URL from your team (GitHub, GitLab, Gitea, or self-hosted).
Always clone via SSH for write access:

```bash
git clone git@<your-git-host>:<org>/{{project_name}}.git
cd {{project_name}}
```

If you only need read access, HTTPS cloning also works:

```bash
git clone https://<your-git-host>/<org>/{{project_name}}.git
```

If you need to set up an SSH key, refer to your hosting provider's documentation
or your organisation's onboarding guide.

---

### Step 4 — Build the project

```bash
cargo build
```

Confirm the build succeeds with no errors.

---

### Step 5 — Run the test suite

```bash
cargo test
```

All tests must pass on a clean checkout. If any fail, raise a bug before continuing.

---

### Step 6 — Build the plugin tools (if using syntek-rust-security plugin)

If `.claude/plugins/` exists in the project:

```bash
cd .claude/plugins
cargo build --release
cd ../..
```

---

### Step 7 — Run the initial security scan

```bash
cargo audit                  # check for known vulnerabilities
cargo deny check             # check licences and bans
cargo geiger --quiet         # count unsafe blocks
```

Review any findings and raise issues as appropriate before starting development.

---

### Step 8 — Verify your editor is configured

Recommended: VS Code with the `rust-analyzer` extension, or any editor with
`rust-analyzer` LSP support.

Check `rust-analyzer` is working:

```bash
rustup component add rust-analyzer
```

---

